Currently, if the webserver that is hosting the deploy images is configured with custom certificate, Ironic will fail to validate the hrefs and eventually the deployment will fail. Currently there is no way to set the certificate. This patch enables it and eventually we can either have another config option similar to "http_root", "http_url" which is something like "http_ca_cert" and use it to validate hrefs. Thanks for the detailed comments. Here are my replies.
1) No this is not a breaking change. As Dmitry pointed out
the default value set by "requests" is True. As per my understanding, the verify argument can take one of the following aligning with requests library.
(a) A boolean value which can be True or False
(b) None
(c) A path to certificate directory or a specific certificate file.

If verify is None it is converted to True by requests and the certificate bundle from the standard path is considered for validation of certificates.
If verify is set to a path then
  a) if the path is a file, it is considered to be the custom certificate
  b) if the path is a directory, all the PEM files in the 
directory are considered for certificate validation

If verify is False, the requests does no certificate validation. Here is a link that gives brief understanding of the particular flag.

https://github.com/psf/requests/blob/2d39c0db054e158767ab4a755476844fe40787e7/requests/sessions.py#L705-#L708

2) Yes. I agree. This should be an operator changeable value and this change is all about paving the way to enable custom certificates. The current change has no impact on the existing functionality. So it will not break the code. 

3) Sure. I will add a release notes.

We have this functionality in IPA when the instance image is referred from a webserver hosted with custom certificate. The following are the links to the code.
a) https://opendev.org/openstack/ironic-python-agent/src/branch/master/ironic_python_agent/extensions/standby.py#L58
b) https://opendev.org/openstack/ironic-python-agent/src/branch/master/ironic_python_agent/utils.py#L430-L444

Just spitballing here, but have we already considered the idea of functions providing their own catalog for the replacements which they include, likely in the same file as each other, and in a standard location within the function e.g. catalog.yaml? The name of a function's catalog could match the name of the function, perhaps with some prefix matching the git repo where the function is defined.

This would make functions more self-contained and self-documenting. This would be similar to how a helm chart provides its own values.yaml schema/defaults. I believe it is also similar to the concept of "setters" (and packages more generally) implemented by "kustomize config" and "kpt", in case that is something we are interested in evolving towards.

For catalog data that needs to be used by multiple functions, presumably that can be accomplished by transitive replacement functionality assuming that is supported?

I thought a bit about making the catalogues function-specific.  There are some benefits like you mention.  I ended up going with combined catalogues for a couple reasons:

1. some catalogues contain data that is inherently shared across functions.  Ex: the openstack endpoints catalogue, where "everything needs to know about keystone".  I think this applies a lot less to the versions catalogue case, though.

2. type/site-level simplicity -- it's a bit easier to manage one catalogue for related widgets, than a dozen (even if in the same file).

If you feel strongly about the granular catalogues, though, let's do discuss pros/cons in a design call - let me know. A bit of "pick your yaml poison" :)

There may be something of a middle ground where there is a shared catalogue (like `versions-airshipctl`), but each function defines its own living example containing only the bits related to the function?  Those couldn't really be "combined" by kustomize, so they'd merely serve as gated examples, and then the `airshipctl-catalogues` function would define a version of the catalogue that contains "everything".
